{"id":"1903.02462","submitter":"Dong Ye","authors":"Michael D. Plummer, Dong Ye and Xiaoya Zha","title":"Dominating maximal outerplane graphs and Hamiltonian plane\n  triangulations","comments":"9 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $G$ be a graph and $\\gamma (G)$ denote the domination number of $G$, i.e.\nthe cardinality of a smallest set of vertices $S$ such that every vertex of $G$\nis either in $S$ or adjacent to a vertex in $S$. Matheson and Tarjan\nconjectured that a plane triangulation with a sufficiently large number $n$ of\nvertices has $\\gamma(G)\\le n/4$. Their conjecture remains unsettled. In the\npresent paper, we show that: (1) a maximal outerplane graph with $n$ vertices\nhas $\\gamma(G)\\le \\lceil \\frac{n+k} 4\\rceil$ where $k$ is the number of pairs\nof consecutive degree 2 vertices separated by distance at least 3 on the\nboundary of $G$; and (2) a Hamiltonian plane triangulation $G$ with $n \\ge 23$\nvertices has $\\gamma (G)\\le 5n/16 $. We also point out and provide\ncounterexamples for several recent published results of Li et al in [Discrete\nAppl. Math.198 (2016) 164-169] on this topic which are incorrect.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Mar 2019 16:07:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-07"}
{"id":"1903.02463","submitter":"Magnus Goffeng","authors":"Magnus Goffeng, Bram Mesland, Adam Rennie","title":"Untwisting twisted spectral triples","comments":"57 pages, full proof of meromorphic extensions added in this version","journal-ref":"International Journal of Mathematics, Vol. 30, No. 14 (2019)","doi":"10.1142/S0129167X19500769","report-no":null,"categories":"math.KT math.OA math.QA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We examine the index data associated to twisted spectral triples and higher\norder spectral triples. In particular, we show that a Lipschitz regular twisted\nspectral triple can always be `logarithmically dampened' through functional\ncalculus, to obtain an ordinary (i.e. untwisted) spectral triple. The same\nprocedure turns higher order spectral triples into spectral triples. We provide\nexamples of highly regular twisted spectral triples with nontrivial index data\nfor which Moscovici's ansatz for a twisted local index formula is identically\nzero.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Mar 2019 16:09:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 24 Sep 2019 07:40:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-21"}
