{"id":"1903.02580","submitter":"Vijay Singh","authors":"Vijay Singh, Martin Tchernookov, Vijay Balasubramanian","title":"What the odor is not: Estimation by elimination","comments":"10 pages; 4 Figures, Supplementary Information","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 104, 024415 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.104.024415","report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.NC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Olfactory systems use a small number of broadly sensitive receptors to\ncombinatorially encode a vast number of odors. We propose a method of decoding\nsuch distributed representations by exploiting a statistical fact: receptors\nthat do not respond to an odor carry more information than receptors that do\nbecause they signal the absence of all odorants that bind to them. Thus, it is\neasier to identify what the odor is not, rather than what the odor is. For\nrealistic numbers of receptors, response functions, and odor complexity, this\nmethod of elimination turns an underconstrained decoding problem into a\nsolvable one, allowing accurate determination of odorants in a mixture and\ntheir concentrations. We construct a neural network realization of our\nalgorithm based on the structure of the olfactory pathway.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Mar 2019 19:02:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 Aug 2019 22:57:19 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 25 Aug 2021 17:51:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-01"}
